│ stop({"edit_points": [[7288, 7296,                                                     │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding the │
│ Issue:\nThe loop-vectorizer crashes on an assertion in                                 │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF() asserting that either the VPlan cost model   │
│ and the legacy cost model select the same VF, or that the VPlan contains additional    │
│ simplifications not accounted for by the legacy cost model. In this reproducer, the    │
│ loop contains a truncation to i1 used by a branch whose condition can be simplified to │
│ a constant (due to an OR with 23), which the VPlan likely simplifies away. The legacy  │
│ model accounts for branch costs differently. Our detection of \"additional             │
│ simplifications\" fails to acknowledge this, causing a false disagreement and          │
│ triggering the assert.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe opt run shows the assertion     │
│ firing directly in computeBestVF(). The code path computes BestFactor via the VPlan    │
│ cost model, then checks against LegacyVF and calls                                     │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(). The debug-only path precomputes costs,        │
│ including branch costs for all loop blocks except the backedge. This precomputation    │
│ marks those branch terminators as skipped in the VPlan cost context.\n\n3. Root Cause  │
│ Analysis:\nplanContainsAdditionalSimplifications() is intended to detect if the VPlan  │
│ has transformations that the legacy model didn't account for. It builds a set of IR    │
│ instructions represented in the VPlan and then returns true if the original loop has   │
│ any instructions not present in the VPlan and not marked to be ignored by the cost     │
│ context or trivial minimal-bitwidth truncations.\n\nHowever, earlier in                │
│ precomputeCosts(), the terminator of each basic block (i.e., branch instructions       │
│ except the backedge) is added to CostCtx.SkipCostComputation. As a result,             │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications() does not consider missing branch instructions  │
│ as evidence of simplifications, even when the VPlan removes/simplifies those branches  │
│ (e.g., constant conditions). In this reproducer, that leads to                         │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications() returning false, despite real simplifications  │
│ in branch control flow, and the assertion fires when BestFactor.Width !=               │
│ LegacyVF.Width.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe should adjust                        │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications() to treat missing branch terminators (excluding │
│ the loop backedge) as additional simplifications, regardless of them being listed in   │
│ SkipCostComputation. This aligns with the intention mentioned in the code comments:    │
│ the number of replicate regions in a VPlan may not directly match the number of        │
│ branches, and branch simplifications are not fully modeled by the legacy cost          │
│ model.\n\nEdit at llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp lines                │
│ 7288-7296:\nReplace the lambda condition to explicitly return true when a BranchInst   │
│ from the loop (excluding the latch/backedge) is not represented in SeenInstrs, even if │
│ skipCostComputation() marks it to be skipped. For other instructions, keep the         │
│ existing checks.\n\nProposed replacement logic:\n- If I is a PHINode, return false.\n- │
│ If I is a BranchInst and BB != OrigLoop->getLoopLatch() and the branch is not in       │
│ SeenInstrs, return true (considered additional simplification).\n- Otherwise, return   │
│ true if the instruction is not in SeenInstrs and not skipped and not a                 │
│ minimal-bitwidth truncation handled by CM.canTruncateToMinimalBitwidth.\n\nThis change │
│ ensures that branch simplifications are counted as \"additional simplifications\" and  │
│ prevents the assertion from firing when the VPlan-based cost model legitimately picks  │
│ a different VF due to control-flow simplifications.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy recognizing  │
│ simplified-away branches as additional simplifications in                              │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(), we correctly allow disagreements between the  │
│ VPlan cost model and the legacy cost model in cases like this reproducer where the     │
│ branch condition is constant-folded in the VPlan. This prevents the assertion from     │
│ triggering and maintains the intended validation path without affecting release        │
│ builds."})                                                                             │
